	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    A reading, from the book of Manipulation</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:lasombra@37thchamber.com">Lasombra Corazon</a> | 
		            4/11/2000 4:10:07 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">The Entrance/mez line of spells is one of the greatest spells we have in our aersonal. The inexperienced, may wonder why.<BR>
<BR>
There is an inconcievable amount of applications that begin with this rare type of stun, I will only clue two, as I must retain some level of self as I write these words...<BR>
<BR>
Can any other class even fathom to boast, the ability for a single character to *completely* debuff a target creature, with any spell they chose, without a single cost to self or life.<BR>
<BR>
Nay.<BR>
<BR>
Application One; The Trojan Horse-<BR>
<BR>
The common application of Entrance that is probably the most valuable, and most used, is traffic control... that is... the ability for an Enchanter with a steady mind and good charisma to control x number of creatures that would normally all be attacking the party at once, turning the situation into a nice linear progression, saving health, mana, and chaos for all in the group.<BR>
<BR>
But the application I speak of here, is an Enchanter's ability to &quot;prepare&quot; a target for the slaughter. This is achieved by starting the battle not with a Tash spell, as commonly done, but an Entrance. Once &quot;mezed&quot; the creature will only respond to 3 events:<BR>
<BR>
1) The spell effect wearing off, where, depending on the spell and target, the creature will develop a portion of hate towards the Enchanter who trapped them in such a state.<BR>
<BR>
2) Being struck by any physical attack. Any form of attack, be it a hit from the pet, or another character, will cause the target to immediately break its state and resume attacking. This makes Entrance a useless spell if your application is to limit the number of times it can attack once melee combat has already begun.  <BR>
<BR>
It should be noted here, that it takes a successful &quot;hit&quot; to break mez. I have personally wittnessed misses occur that did not cause the creature to revert.<BR>
<BR>
3) Being afflicted by any spell that causes &quot;damage&quot; to the creatures health. This includes all direct damage spells, and DOTs.<BR>
<BR>
It should be noted here, that even if a creature is mezed after a damage over time spell is applied, the creature will break the next time the spell &quot;ticks&quot; and the target inflicts damage. This is to say that a DOT'ed creature is useless to stop, and should be killed before others who can more readily be controlled.<BR>
<BR>
It should also be noted here, that it takes a successful application of damage to break. I have also wittnesed instances where the creature fully resisted the damage spell being cast at it, and therefore did not break from its mezzed state.<BR>
<BR>
So then, amidst those three laws, the wise enchanter learns what exists outside the bounds of these rules.<BR>
<BR>
I have personally entranced vile spell casting Gloomwater Mermaids in Kedge Keep, and, as the group stood ready, stacked Tashania, Languid Pace, Curse of the Simple Mind, and five (5) casts of Mana Sieve. All of this, in the duration of one (1) stun, and all of this, as the mermaid stood there helpless, and unattacking.<BR>
<BR>
The end result? A mermaid that was completely drained of her mana, having not cast a single spell in the combat that followed, while both being afflicted with a terribly slow attack rate, and lowered magic resistance. All for free, all for not having lost a single hit point. Not bad.<BR>
<BR>
Expand on this path, and you shall discover things you never thought possible.<BR>
<BR>
Also, as a commandment to this rule, do note that every debuff you stack adds anger to that creatre. Stack enough, and you may have signed your death certificate as not even the mightiest warrior taunt could save you. It is for this reason that a wise enchanter casts Memory Blur as his final stack, and instructs others in the party to Taunt the creature repetedly, until it breaks naturally and attacks them, rather than you.<BR>
<BR>
Application 2; The Spent Caster-<BR>
<BR>
It is rediculous to say that, in combat, an Enchanter's fight is all or nothing... that is, either the target dies, the Enchanter dies, or the Enchanter zones, and the fight is neutral. This is true for most other classes, with the exception of Monks and Necromancers who can feign death, etc to end combat.<BR>
<BR>
But an Enchanter who grows weary or spent in battle shall always reserve the last bubble of mana for the purposes of Entrance, upon which a successful cast will render the target immoble while the Enchanter sits, with Clarity, and regains mana. It should be known that at higher levels, you could potentially keep a creature chain-mezed while you gain back nearly all of your mana; as you will regain more mana between casts than what Entrance takes to cast.<BR>
<BR>
This is the small offset we carry to the frustrating idea that we cannot do partial damage, and that even myself, near 50, I have still cast damage spells on level 8 skeletons and have gotten fully resisted. There is nothing more frustrating than running out of mana in a situation like this, because your target took 0 damage for the 160 mana you just burned. If this happens, simply entrance him/her, and sit to regain that wasted mana.<BR>
<BR>
I must move on, I will possibly post more in the future, but again I must retain some secrets and techniques as to keep myself in a favorable state when groups seek an Enchanter... but know that the limits of our spell lines lie only in the hands of creativity and experimentation.... <BR>
<BR>
Lasombra Corazon;<BR>
Guild Leader, Illumin Cathari;<BR>
Solusek Ro Server
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
